04952nam a22008055i 9780231504713DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2012    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315047137 a10.7312/moin160362doi  a(DE-B1597)459142  a(OCoLC)818814875  a(OCoLC)979573786  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aJC375b.M65 2015 7aREL0370002bisacsh04a297.2722231 aMoin, A. Azfar, eauthor.14aThe Millennial Sovereign :bSacred Kingship and Sainthood in Islam /cA. Azfar Moin. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2012] 4cÂ©2012  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSouth Asia Across the Disciplines00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tList of Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Transliteration -- t1. Introduction: Islam and the Millennium -- t2. The Lord of Conjunction: Sacrality and Sovereignty in the Age of Timur -- t3. The Crown of Dreams: Sufis and Princes in Sixteenth-Century Iran -- t4. The Alchemical Court: The Beginnings of the Mughal Imperial Cult -- t5. The Millennial Sovereign: The Troubled Unveiling of the Savior Monarch -- t6. The Throne of Time: The Painted Miracles of the Saint Emperor -- t7. Conclusion: The Graffiti Under the Throne -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAt the end of the sixteenth century and the turn of the first Islamic millennium, the powerful Mughal emperor Akbar declared himself the most sacred being on earth. The holiest of all saints and above the distinctions of religion, he styled himself as the messiah reborn. Yet the Mughal emperor was not alone in doing so. In this field-changing study, A. Azfar Moin explores why Muslim sovereigns in this period began to imitate the exalted nature of Sufi saints. Uncovering a startling yet widespread phenomenon, he shows how the charismatic pull of sainthood (wilayat)-rather than the draw of religious law (sharia) or holy war (jihad)-inspired a new style of sovereignty in Islam. A work of history richly informed by the anthropology of religion and art, The Millennial Sovereign traces how royal dynastic cults and shrine-centered Sufism came together in the imperial cultures of Timurid Central Asia, Safavid Iran, and Mughal India. By juxtaposing imperial chronicles, paintings, and architecture with theories of sainthood, apocalyptic treatises, and manuals on astrology and magic, Moin uncovers a pattern of Islamic politics shaped by Sufi and millennial motifs. He shows how alchemical symbols and astrological rituals enveloped the body of the monarch, casting him as both spiritual guide and material lord. Ultimately, Moin offers a striking new perspective on the history of Islam and the religious and political developments linking South Asia and Iran in early-modern times.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aKings and rulersxReligious aspectsxIslam. 0aMuslim saints. 0aSovereigntyxReligious aspectsxIslam. 7aRELIGION / Islam / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066254208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311045952440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/moin16036423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231504713.jpg  a978-3-11-044247-2  CUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013  a978-3-11-045952-4  CUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014c2000d2014  a978-3-11-066254-2  CUP eBook Package 2000-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPAL